<br>
It either drops you between the second and third person on the hate list or 500 pooints down the list, whichever is greater.<br>
<br>
Positioning also has an impact on hate.  A rogue should stand as far away from the mob and still be able to hit, while the main tank should stand just about on top if the mob.  If the tank is an equal distance away as the rogue, then it's pure hate.<br>
<br>
Personally, I carry about four different weapons with me.  If aggro becomes too difficult to avoid, for whatever reason, I'll switch out to a less damaging combo.  I want to drop damage, but never resort to hand to hand if possible.<br>
<br>
Now back to Uinin's question...<br>
<br>
A bard will never be truely considered a damage dealer.  To train up your skills, just find the lowest delay weapons possible for the skill you need to raise.  There are some nice, inexpensive ones out there if you know what to look for.  A bard's true power is in his/her songs.  You really have to have some major gear to consistantly outdamage your songs, once you reach your 40s.  So just get some training weapons and ask your group if you can train while fighting.  Then use your judgement if training will endanger the group.<br>
